ABAC - Attribute-Based Access Control

Simple Meaning
ABAC gives access based on user attributes like department, location, role, or time of day.
Example rule: If you are in HR department and sitting in Lahore office, then you get access.

How ABAC Works

Check user attributes

If attributes match the rule → Access allowed
If attributes do not match → Access denied

Example Rule in ABAC
This rule means: User "saad" can create pods in namespace "default".

Field	        Value
User	        saad
Namespace	    default
Resource	    pods
Verb	        create

ABAC vs RBAC

Feature	        ABAC	                                        RBAC
Based on	    User attributes (department, location, role)	Roles and role bindings
Complexity	    High, hard to manage	                        Simple, easy to manage
Popularity	    Rarely used	                                    Very popular, standard
Example	        If user is from HR and Lahore, allow	        If user has role "developer", allow

Why ABAC is Less Popular

Rules become very complex when you have many attributes
Hard to understand who has what access

Difficult to audit

RBAC is simpler and covers most use cases

Real Benefit for IT Working
ABAC is useful when you need very fine grained access based on user properties like location, time, or department. But for most clusters, RBAC is enough and much easier to manage.

